# StarCaster Project — Cursor Rules & Coding Conventions

## Project Structure
```
starcaster/
  server.js                 # Local dev HTTP server only
  api/[...slug].js          # Vercel serverless entry → routes/index.js
  routes/                   # API modules: { handle, manifest }
  lib/                      # Stores, supabase, config, projectScope, AI helpers
  public/
    index.html              # Generated — edit src/ instead
    app.js                  # Module registry & boot (PROTECTED)
    js/*.js                 # Feature modules (window.App.*)
    bundle.js               # React campaigns island only
    styles.css              # Built from src/css/main.css
  src/
    layout.html             # App shell template
    pages/*.html            # Page partials (INJECT_PAGES)
    css/                    # Authoritative stylesheets
  components/               # React (campaigns only)
  scripts/                  # build_html, migrations, imports
  docs/                     # AI_AGENT_HANDOFF.md, UI_STANDARDS.md, *.sql
  data/                     # Local JSON stores (gitignored secrets); not for prod writes
  ai-daemon/                # Separate agent service — not main app
```

## Frontend Module Pattern
1. Create `public/js/myModule.js` with `manifest: { id, label, pageId, pagePrefixes? }`, `init()`, optional `refresh()` / `onPageActivated()`.
2. Add `<script src="/js/myModule.js">` in `src/layout.html` before `app.js`.
3. Register in `public/app.js` → `App.manifests`.
4. Add or extend markup in `src/pages/*.html`, then `npm run build:html`.

Shared state: `public/js/core.js` — `App.state`, `App.api()`, project switcher, navigation.

## Backend Route Pattern
1. Create `routes/myModule.js` exporting `{ handle(req, res, pathname, method), manifest: { id, label, prefixes } }`.
2. Import and append to `ROUTE_MODULES` in `routes/index.js`.
3. Implement store in `lib/` using `sbQuery()` and `projectScope` helpers when data is tenant-scoped.
4. Add `docs/my_table_setup.sql`; wire table names in `lib/supabase.js` if needed.

## API Conventions
- Envelope: `{ ok: true, data }` / `{ ok: false, error: { message, code?, details? } }`.
- Authenticated requests: session cookie `app_session`; project header `x-project-id`.
- Rate limits: global in dispatcher; expensive ops add per-route limits.
- Never expose `SUPABASE_SERVICE_KEY` to the browser.

## Supabase & Multitenancy
- New project-scoped tables: `project_id`, `owner_user_id`, scoped queries via `lib/projectScope.js`.
- Email/slug uniqueness is per-project, not global.
- Legacy `NULL project_id` rows may still appear via compat filter — prefer backfill + strict scope for new code.
- Check `docs/` SQL before assuming a column exists.

## Naming (code vs UI)
| UI | Code / DB |
|----|-----------|
| Builder | `develop`, `develop_*` |
| Messaging: Topics | `topics` (not `category`) |
| Ask Roger | `devAgent`, `/api/develop/roger/*` |
| StarCaster | package `starcaster`, title in `src/layout.html` |

## File-Backed Stores (avoid for new features)
Do not add new production features that write `data/*.json`. Known file stores: direct acquire runs, engage social posts, acquire job mirror, auth/projects fallback, api settings, training JSON, some develop fallbacks.

## Vercel & Deployment
- `vercel.json` must keep API rewrite to `api/[...slug]`.
- Deploy: `git push` then `vercel --prod` per `docs/DEPLOYMENT.md`.
- Required env: see `docs/VERCEL_CUTOVER.md` and `lib/config.js`.

## Rich Text (Tiptap)
- Used in Builder/messaging editors where present; keep package versions aligned in `package.json`.
- Custom extensions may exist in builder tooling — follow existing patterns in `scripts/build_richtext_bundle.mjs`.

## Common Pitfalls
- Do not edit `public/index.html` for structural changes without running `build:html` from `src/`.
- Do not remove or simplify `vercel.json` API routes (caused production 404s).
- Do not treat `public/app.js` as disposable when experimenting with React.
- Do not use `ai-daemon/sandbox/isit-app/docs/` as schema source — use `docs/` at repo root.
- `polls.js` is loaded in layout but may need explicit registration in `App.manifests` when wiring UI.
- Supabase free tier pauses after inactivity — resume from dashboard if connections fail.
- Production: env vars override `data/api_settings.json` for secrets.
- **Builder module types — dual registration required:** Adding a new module type to `lib/builder-client/builder-template.ts` (the TypeScript source) is not enough. `lib/builder/template.js` is a separately generated CJS bundle used server-side for page save/load normalization. If `normalizeModuleType` in the server bundle doesn't include the new type, the server coerces it to `"text"` on every load, silently replacing the module. After editing `builder-template.ts`, always run `node scripts/build_template_bundle.mjs` to regenerate `lib/builder/template.js`.
- **`public/styles.css` is a build artifact — never edit it directly, never assume CSS edits are live without a rebuild.** All stylesheet source lives in `src/css/` as partials (`_variables.css`, `_tables.css`, `legacy.css`, etc.) imported by `src/css/main.css`. The file `public/styles.css` is compiled from that source by esbuild on every build (`npx esbuild src/css/main.css --bundle --outfile=public/styles.css`). Edits made directly to `public/styles.css` are silently wiped on the next deploy. Edits made to `src/css/*.css` are invisible until esbuild is re-run. The correct workflow: edit `src/css/<partial>.css` → run `npx esbuild src/css/main.css --bundle --outfile=public/styles.css` → commit both the source partial and the rebuilt `public/styles.css`.

## Agent Documentation
- **Start here:** `docs/AI_AGENT_HANDOFF.md` (canonical; supersedes older handoffs and wrong paths).
- UI deep-dive: `docs/UI_STANDARDS.md`, `docs/STYLE_GUIDE.md`.
- Incidents: `docs/roger_diagnostic_report.md`.
- Tri-agent protocol: `docs/tri_agent_protocol_v1.md`.

## Reference Implementation
Use **Normie** (`~/WebApps/normie`) as the live tenant/project when validating end-to-end StarCaster flows (presence, promotion, engagement). Keep product boundaries clear: Normie-specific token/branding stays in Normie unless explicitly ported.
